<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="9" type="taxonomic notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="9">Taxonomic notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="9">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hilliard &amp; B. L. Burtt in Notes Roy. Bot. Gard., Edinburgh 37 (2): 287" authorityYear="1979" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Cynoglossum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Cynoglossum spelaeum" order="Boraginales" pageId="0" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="spelaeum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="9">Cynoglossum spelaeum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is quite distinctive among the southern African species having uniquely shaped (i.e., spatulate to obtuse) and coloured (i.e., deep green adaxial surface, grey green abaxial surface) leaves, that almost seem leathery but contain few soft trichomes. It is also the only species among the southern African species that has completely white flowers. Although 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/BDJ.3.e4831" author="Hilger, HH" journalOrPublisher="Biodiversity Data Journal" pageId="0" pageNumber="9" pagination="1 - 23" refId="B13" refString="Hilger, HH, Greuter, W, Stier, V, 2015. Taxa and names in Cynoglossum sensu lato (Boraginaceae, Cynoglosseae): An annotated, synonymic inventory, with links to the protologues and mention of original material. Biodiversity Data Journal 3: 1 - 23, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/BDJ.3.e4831" title="Taxa and names in Cynoglossum sensu lato (Boraginaceae, Cynoglosseae): An annotated, synonymic inventory, with links to the protologues and mention of original material." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/BDJ.3.e4831" volume="3" year="2015">Hilger et al. (2015)</bibRefCitation>
indicated that the species does not belong to genus 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Cynoglossum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Cynoglossum" order="Boraginales" pageId="0" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="9">Cynoglossum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, they did not elaborate the reasons for the exclusion. Nonetheless, the species fits the generic description of four glochidiate nutlets that are adapted for zoochory. In addition, preliminary molecular data (
